 <a href="/content/linux-vs-bullshit" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"><img src="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/ufiles/imagecache/teaser/nodeimage/story/nobull.jpg" alt="" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-teaser" width="100" height="100" /></a> 
  
  


      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/linux-vs-bullshit" title="Linux vs. Bullshit">Linux vs. Bullshit</a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/doc-searls" title="View user profile.">Doc Searls</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Sep 05, 2013 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_881 first"><a href="/tag/advertising" rel="tag" title="">Advertising</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_282"><a href="/tag/business" rel="tag" title="">Business</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_880 last"><a href="/tag/marketing" rel="tag" title="">Marketing</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/linux-vs-bullshit" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>
Linux doesn't lie, any more than gravity lies, or geology lies, or atmosphere
lies. Like those other natural things, Linux has no guile, no agenda beyond
supporting the entirety of use-space. In rough words, there's no bullshit about
it, and that's one reason it gets used. Let me explain.
<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/linux-vs-bullshit"> more>></a></span></p>
  </div>



  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_comments first last"><a href="/content/linux-vs-bullshit#comments" title="Jump to the first comment of this posting.">23 comments</a></li>
</ul>
