 <a href="/content/dear-hotels-quit-being-holes" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"><img src="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/ufiles/imagecache/teaser/nodeimage/story/11533f1_0.jpg" alt="" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-teaser" width="100" height="100" /></a> 
  
  


      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/dear-hotels-quit-being-holes" title="Dear Hotels: Quit Being A-holes">Dear Hotels: Quit Being A-holes</a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/doc-searls" title="View user profile.">Doc Searls</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Aug 06, 2013 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_328 first"><a href="/tag/mobile" rel="tag" title="">Mobile</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_486 last"><a href="/tag/wi-fi" rel="tag" title="">Wi-Fi</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/dear-hotels-quit-being-holes" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>
<a href="http://frankston.com">Bob Frankston</a> says connectivity will eventually become
<a href="http://frankston.com/public/?name=AmbientConnectivity">"ambient"&mdash;something we just assume</a>, much as we assume electricity, water,
sewage treatment and other infrastructural conveniences. None of those
conveniences are free of cost, of course, and we pay for them one way or
another.<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/dear-hotels-quit-being-holes"> more>></a></span></p>
  </div>



  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_comments first last"><a href="/content/dear-hotels-quit-being-holes#comments" title="Jump to the first comment of this posting.">25 comments</a></li>
</ul>
